[link: #table-of-content] —ظXarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/blog/2024-07-29-nushell_0_96_1.mdظ@a3531d4de33a388e4ad632fc5970e3440c82150c82f85b8f838ec446128da733µtitle: Nushell 0.96.1‘،]ع¨``$in``
[link: #table-of-content] 0.96.0 changed how 
``$in``
-containing expressions worked to make them more consistent, but we missed checking the expressions contained within ranges. Piping to a range expression containing 
``$in``
 has now been fixed:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nushell"))
3 | 0..$in | each { print }

```
Thanks to 
[link: https://github.com/maxim-uvarov] Maxim Uvarov
 for finding and reporting this issue!
’گگعضTitle: title: Nushell 0.96.1
Path: ]
Content:
``$in``
[link: #table-of-content] 0.96.0 changed how 
``$in``
-containing expressions worked to make them more consistent, but we missed checking the expressions contained within ranges. Piping to a range expression containing 
``$in``
 has now been fixed:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nushell"))
3 | 0..$in | each { print }

```
Thanks to 
[link: https://github.com/maxim-uvarov] Maxim Uvarov
 for finding and reporting this issue!
—ظXarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/blog/2024-07-29-nushell_0_96_1.mdظ@f4949bfdab888ddf404da07b4006f7038b54300301d13e8241cfec27f14504b0µtitle: Nushell 0.96.1‘،]عت[link: #table-of-content] A bug was found by user 
``warp``
 over on Discord in the new internal representation engine that we introduced as a preview in 0.96.0. Subexpressions (i.e., expressions in parentheses) should not have any impact on the capturing behavior of external commands, but this was implemented incorrectly. In 0.96.0, the following code produced no output when run with IR even though it should have still resulted in a message being printed:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
(nu -c 'print foo'); null

```
This was most noticeable when running some kind of interactive command, as it would result in stdout not being a TTY. We have fixed the IR implementation to match the behavior of the AST evaluator.
’گگعّTitle: title: Nushell 0.96.1
Path: ]
Content:
[link: #table-of-content] A bug was found by user 
``warp``
 over on Discord in the new internal representation engine that we introduced as a preview in 0.96.0. Subexpressions (i.e., expressions in parentheses) should not have any impact on the capturing behavior of external commands, but this was implemented incorrectly. In 0.96.0, the following code produced no output when run with IR even though it should have still resulted in a message being printed:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
(nu -c 'print foo'); null

```
This was most noticeable when running some kind of interactive command, as it would result in stdout not being a TTY. We have fixed the IR implementation to match the behavior of the AST evaluator.
—ظXarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/blog/2024-07-29-nushell_0_96_1.mdظ@897062d289bf29c96b810f7510b700a3c6dc465fe2f85f41ea36d5fb2d76c0dfµtitle: Nushell 0.96.1‘،]عr``CallDecl``
[link: #table-of-content] A memory leak was present when using the new 
[link: ../contributor-book/plugin_protocol_reference.md#calldecl-engine-call] ``CallDecl``
 engine call
 from plugins. The arguments included in the call would persist in memory until the plugin call ended, rather than being removed at the end of the engine call. This has been fixed.
’گگع Title: title: Nushell 0.96.1
Path: ]
Content:
``CallDecl``
[link: #table-of-content] A memory leak was present when using the new 
[link: ../contributor-book/plugin_protocol_reference.md#calldecl-engine-call] ``CallDecl``
 engine call
 from plugins. The arguments included in the call would persist in memory until the plugin call ended, rather than being removed at the end of the engine call. This has been fixed.
—ظXarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/blog/2024-07-29-nushell_0_96_1.mdظ@6289114c2aa216bae5938455c6777a527ad2ced2c15e2c65f712e404e889e41aµtitle: Nushell 0.96.1‘،]؛[link: #table-of-content] ’گگظHTitle: title: Nushell 0.96.1
